WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
Next, please join me in welcoming Daniel Falbel from RStudio.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:20.760
Hello, I'm Daniel, and today I'm going to talk about what's new in TensorFlow for R.

00:00:21.760 --> 00:00:25.760
First, a quick recap on what's TensorFlow.

00:00:25.760 --> 00:00:30.760
Well, TensorFlow is an open source platform for machine learning.

00:00:30.760 --> 00:00:34.759
It's especially useful for deep learning.

00:00:34.759 --> 00:00:44.759
So, it has fast implementations of most common operations in deep learning, like convolutions, for example.

00:00:44.759 --> 00:00:56.759
And it's very efficient for both CPUs, GPUs, and even TPUs, which is the Google hardware for deep learning.

00:00:56.759 --> 00:01:02.759
It provides automatic differentiation, which is also very useful for deep learning.

00:01:02.759 --> 00:01:05.760
And it's really production-ready.

00:01:05.760 --> 00:01:20.760
So, inside the TensorFlow ecosystem, there are multiple ways to deploy your models to even mobile devices, cloud platforms, and all of this.

00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:31.760
Well, TensorFlow is mostly a Python project with a lot of things in the ecosystem.

00:01:31.760 --> 00:01:35.760
And I'm going to talk about the TensorFlow for R package.

00:01:35.760 --> 00:01:40.760
And we are spread across multiple R packages.

00:01:40.760 --> 00:01:52.760
There is the TensorFlow R package, which provides mostly the basic access to the TensorFlow model and installation functions and things like this.

00:01:53.760 --> 00:02:04.760
There is the Keras R package, which wraps the tf.keras model, which is the recommended way to start using TensorFlow.

00:02:04.760 --> 00:02:08.759
It's like a higher-level API to use TensorFlow.

00:02:08.759 --> 00:02:20.759
And tf.datasets, which wraps the tf.data model, which uses it to load and preprocess that data for deep learning.

00:02:20.759 --> 00:02:34.759
And we have a lot of other packages in the ecosystem, like tf.hub, tf.probability, tf.js, tf.autograph, and tf.auto.keras, which I'm going to talk about.

00:02:34.759 --> 00:02:36.759
So, what's new?

00:02:36.759 --> 00:02:40.759
There's a lot of packages, and things are moving fast.

00:02:40.759 --> 00:02:46.759
So, we have support for TensorFlow 2.0.

00:02:46.759 --> 00:03:02.759
So, before 2.0, TensorFlow was working like you had to define all your graph computation, and then you executed it.

00:03:02.759 --> 00:03:10.759
And this is a programming model that is hard to think about, usually.

00:03:10.759 --> 00:03:16.759
And with 2.0, it's much easier because of the eager execution.

00:03:16.759 --> 00:03:19.759
So, before, you needed to write code like this.

00:03:19.759 --> 00:03:24.759
So, you write all computation, and then you executed it.

00:03:24.759 --> 00:03:31.759
And now, it works just like normal R arrays.

00:03:31.759 --> 00:03:39.759
Other changes in 2.0 are like API cleanup and things like this.

00:03:39.759 --> 00:03:50.759
There is this new package by Thomas Kalinowski, which is called tf.autograph, which allows us to write conditional loops.

00:03:50.759 --> 00:03:55.759
And like if, and while, and for statements.

00:03:55.759 --> 00:04:00.759
Just like an R if statement, which is much easier.

00:04:00.759 --> 00:04:04.759
And this is very efficient, also, for TensorFlow.

00:04:04.759 --> 00:04:12.759
So, before, you needed to write code like this, with all functional conditionals.

00:04:12.759 --> 00:04:22.760
And now, you can just write an if statement, and it will be converted to TensorFlow code.

00:04:22.760 --> 00:04:32.760
In tf.datasets, which allows to load and preprocess that data, we have this new feature spec interface.

00:04:32.760 --> 00:04:39.760
And this is useful for tabular data, and for using tabular data in deep learning models.

00:04:39.760 --> 00:04:50.760
So, it works like, it has a similar interface to like recipes, the tidy models package.

00:04:50.760 --> 00:04:56.760
And so, you just define what transformations you want to do on your tabular data.

00:04:56.760 --> 00:05:05.760
And then, you fit this specification, which means it will find all possible vocabulary and like scaling,

00:05:05.760 --> 00:05:12.760
or find the normalizing constants for your numeric variables, for example.

00:05:12.760 --> 00:05:20.760
And then, you can just use this layer dense features function in Keras.

00:05:20.760 --> 00:05:28.760
And this will make all the transformations directly on the TensorFlow graph.

00:05:28.760 --> 00:05:33.760
So, it's much easier to deploy this kind of models.

00:05:36.760 --> 00:05:40.760
Next, we have some minor changes in tf.datasets.

00:05:40.760 --> 00:05:49.760
Like, if you ever use a data set map, you needed to write a function to like per map.

00:05:49.760 --> 00:05:58.760
And now, you can use the per style lambda functions, which like simplifies a bit the code.

00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:05.760
And you can also pass, if you used tf.datasets before,

00:06:05.760 --> 00:06:14.760
you needed to use the make iterator one-shot function to create an iterator for your TensorFlow data set.

00:06:14.760 --> 00:06:19.760
And now, you can pass this directly to Keras, and it will just work.

00:06:22.760 --> 00:06:27.760
Another cool new package is the tf.hub package,

00:06:27.760 --> 00:06:36.760
which allows us to use any pre-trained models from this website here, tf.hub.dev.

00:06:36.760 --> 00:06:44.760
And so, people train their models in large data sets,

00:06:44.760 --> 00:06:50.760
and provide them the pre-trained models in a useful format.

00:06:50.760 --> 00:06:54.760
And then, you can just use it as a new Keras layer.

00:06:55.760 --> 00:06:59.760
So, you have the URL for a model.

00:06:59.760 --> 00:07:03.760
In this case, it's the mobile net model.

00:07:03.760 --> 00:07:11.760
And you have this layer hub function that just takes the model URL.

00:07:11.760 --> 00:07:22.760
And then, so, this model is taking an image and returning a feature vector representing this image.

00:07:22.760 --> 00:07:31.760
And you can just plug a dense layer, for example, to make a classification using these pre-trained models.

00:07:31.760 --> 00:07:36.760
It also includes models for text and video.

00:07:38.760 --> 00:07:45.760
tf.hub also provides recipes integration, the tidy models recipes.

00:07:46.760 --> 00:07:53.760
So, if you are familiar with recipes, you have all these step functions.

00:07:53.760 --> 00:07:57.760
And there's a new step, pre-trained text embedding.

00:07:57.760 --> 00:08:03.760
And you can just plug a pre-trained text model, for example.

00:08:04.760 --> 00:08:06.760
Oh, sorry.

00:08:09.760 --> 00:08:15.760
For example, here, it's a pre-trained model in the Google News data set,

00:08:15.760 --> 00:08:19.760
which is a very large data set of news.

00:08:20.760 --> 00:08:28.760
And it will convert raw text to a feature vector that you can just use in your machine learning model.

00:08:29.760 --> 00:08:36.760
And then, you can feed logistic regression, for example, using this feature vector.

00:08:39.760 --> 00:08:44.760
Okay, in Keras, we have these new text pre-processing layers.

00:08:44.760 --> 00:08:51.760
Well, it starts in tf2.0, 2.1, sorry.

00:08:51.760 --> 00:08:54.760
And it changes.

00:08:54.760 --> 00:09:01.760
Before, the Keras pre-processing functions are all based in SciPy and NumPy.

00:09:01.760 --> 00:09:09.760
So, in order to use the functions in Keras, you needed also to have a Python...

00:09:12.760 --> 00:09:20.760
To deploy models that use a text pre-processing function in Keras, you needed to have a Python runtime.

00:09:20.760 --> 00:09:25.760
And now, they are built in the TensorFlow graph.

00:09:25.760 --> 00:09:35.760
So, you can build models using this layer text vectorization, and the deployment will be much easier.

00:09:35.760 --> 00:09:40.760
So, it works just like a normal Keras layer.

00:09:40.760 --> 00:09:46.760
You define what are the main parameters.

00:09:46.760 --> 00:09:54.760
And there's a new step called adapt, which will, for example, find all different words in your text data.

00:09:54.760 --> 00:10:03.760
Or it will find the maximum length of each text and things like this.

00:10:03.760 --> 00:10:08.760
And then, you can just plug this layer in your Keras model.

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:20.760
So, your model will input strings, and you just plug like a normal Keras model.

00:10:23.760 --> 00:10:37.760
Another cool new package by Seagrid is tf.probability, which provides a lot of statistical computation and probabilistic functions.

00:10:37.760 --> 00:10:49.760
It's built on top of TensorFlow, so it provides GPU and CPU and even TPU implementation for most things, which is great and fast.

00:10:49.760 --> 00:11:04.760
And I want to show you just this layer distribution function that you can plug in your Keras model as an usual Keras layer.

00:11:04.760 --> 00:11:14.760
And instead of predicting a single value for each observation, you can, for example, predict a normal distribution for each observation.

00:11:14.760 --> 00:11:18.760
So, you can calculate standard deviation and stuff.

00:11:18.760 --> 00:11:25.760
So, this opens a great scope for deep learning.

00:11:25.760 --> 00:11:32.760
You can see more in the release blog post, which is linked here.

00:11:34.760 --> 00:11:38.760
There is AutoKeras, a package by Juan Cruz.

00:11:38.760 --> 00:11:55.760
And it interfaces R to the AutoKeras package in Python, which uses AutoML techniques to build machine learning models.

00:11:56.760 --> 00:12:07.760
So, instead of defining all your Keras layers and how they are connected, you can just use this model image classifier and how many different models you want to try.

00:12:07.760 --> 00:12:13.760
And it will try to get a good model for your dataset.

00:12:13.760 --> 00:12:31.760
There is TFDS, a new package, which is very experimental yet, but it allows you to load public datasets in the TensorFlow datasets format.

00:12:31.760 --> 00:12:49.760
Which, for example, you can load ImageNet using TFDS without touching all the, I don't know, 100 gigabytes of images and how to download them and how to preprocess and everything.

00:12:49.760 --> 00:12:55.760
So, it's much easier to just test your machine learning model.

00:12:56.760 --> 00:13:07.760
And it provides this split API that you can say, like, I want to split my data in training, validation, and test that directly.

00:13:07.760 --> 00:13:19.760
So, it's a nice package when you are learning new things, when you are trying your deep learning model.

00:13:20.760 --> 00:13:37.760
We are also providing some model packages, which, like, we took some commonly used deep learning models and packaged R wrappers for them.

00:13:37.760 --> 00:13:43.760
For example, the GP2 package by Javier Luraski.

00:13:43.760 --> 00:13:55.760
And the GP2 model is a deep learning model by OpenAI, which takes, like, a prompt string.

00:13:55.760 --> 00:14:07.760
And it can, like, complete this string with a text that really makes sense, and it's pretty incredible.

00:14:08.760 --> 00:14:19.760
We also implemented some deep learning models using raw Keras layers, just for...

00:14:22.760 --> 00:14:28.760
So, it's easier to learn, and you can see advanced modeling code in Keras.

00:14:29.760 --> 00:14:33.760
So, there's UNet, which is an image segmentation model.

00:14:33.760 --> 00:14:42.760
And DenseNet, which is a convolutional neural network architecture that was famous, like, maybe two years ago.

00:14:42.760 --> 00:14:45.760
And deep learning is very fast.

00:14:45.760 --> 00:14:58.760
And there are also community-contributed models, like the RBERT by Jonathan and John Harmon,

00:14:58.760 --> 00:15:06.760
which provides an implementation of the BERT model, which is a Google model for text embedding.

00:15:07.760 --> 00:15:25.760
We also have the TensorFlow for Art blog, which Sigrid writes many, many articles showing the state-of-the-art of TensorFlow and deep learning with very detailed explanations.

00:15:25.760 --> 00:15:27.760
Thank you.

00:15:27.760 --> 00:15:29.760
Thank you.

00:15:39.760 --> 00:15:42.760
Thank you very much, and we've got a few minutes for questions.

00:15:43.760 --> 00:15:51.760
So, one of the questions on Slido is, classification and regression problems are very accessible via R's interface to TensorFlow.

00:15:51.760 --> 00:15:56.760
How about survival problems, such as time-to-event outcomes?

00:15:58.760 --> 00:15:59.760
Such as? Sorry.

00:15:59.760 --> 00:16:01.760
Time-to-event outcomes, survival.

00:16:01.760 --> 00:16:02.760
Yeah.

00:16:03.760 --> 00:16:19.760
Usually, deep learning is very flexible, so these time-to-event models can be modeled by just changing your loss function.

00:16:19.760 --> 00:16:26.760
So, you can cover this with deep learning, with the Keras package.

00:16:26.760 --> 00:16:28.760
There's a blog post by Sigrid.

00:16:28.760 --> 00:16:39.760
Actually, that would not be deep learning, but that would use TensorFlow probability or the RREP IDF probability, and that would be Monte Carlo modeling to do that.

00:16:39.760 --> 00:16:44.760
We have a blog post. I think it's called, like, oh, how is it called? Anyone know?

00:16:46.760 --> 00:16:48.760
Censored data something.

00:16:48.760 --> 00:16:52.760
Yeah, censored data, right? You wrote this blog post.

00:16:52.760 --> 00:16:58.760
Yeah, and this uses TensorFlow probability, so not deep learning, but also cool stuff.

00:17:01.760 --> 00:17:05.760
What are our studio's plans to support Torch or PyTorch?

00:17:06.760 --> 00:17:24.760
I don't know. We have worked. I have experimented with Torch, like, a year ago with the C++ API, but I'm not sure if we are going to move forward Torch for now.

00:17:27.760 --> 00:17:30.760
Well, someone wants to know, what are you working on right now?

00:17:31.760 --> 00:17:36.760
Yeah. TensorFlow is a large ecosystem.

00:17:36.760 --> 00:17:42.760
Like, there's always a lot of stuff that we want to work on.

00:17:42.760 --> 00:17:57.760
Like, there's this dopamine library for reinforcement learning, which is something we would like to work, and there's also a lot of work with DF probability still, so, yeah.

00:17:58.760 --> 00:18:10.760
All right, one more. Is the plan to track the Python interface to TensorFlow, or will the R extras mean that Python users won't recognize R-based TensorFlow code?

00:18:11.760 --> 00:18:21.760
Yeah. Like, Keras, our package, tries to keep track of all Python changes.

00:18:21.760 --> 00:18:29.760
For example, these new text preprocessing layers, and there will be image preprocessing layers and all this kind of stuff.

00:18:29.760 --> 00:18:36.760
We will try to always keep track of the Keras API.

00:18:36.760 --> 00:18:53.760
But we like to add, like, the R way of doing things also, like the feature spec interface, which doesn't exist in the Python implementation.

00:18:53.760 --> 00:18:56.760
Excellent. Thank you. So, let's give another round of applause.

00:19:06.760 --> 00:19:09.760
Thank you.

